/* ============================================================================
   linux+ :: content/domain5.js
   Lazy-loaded textbook reading module for XK0-006 Domain 5 (Troubleshooting).
   Populates LINUXPLUS.reading[5]. Loaded on demand by app.js.
   ============================================================================ */
window.LINUXPLUS = window.LINUXPLUS || {}; LINUXPLUS.reading = LINUXPLUS.reading || {};
LINUXPLUS.reading[5] = [];
LINUXPLUS.reading[5].push(
  {heading:"The CompTIA Troubleshooting Methodology", body:"<p>Troubleshooting is 22 percent of the XK0-006 exam, and CompTIA expects you to apply a disciplined, repeatable process rather than guessing. The methodology is the same one used across every CompTIA exam, but on Linux it is anchored by one habit above all others: <strong>read the logs first</strong>. A frantic administrator who reboots before reading <code>journalctl -xe</code> destroys the very evidence that would have explained the failure. The process exists to keep you from skipping steps under pressure, and the exam rewards candidates who can name the correct <em>next</em> step in a scenario rather than the most dramatic one.</p><h3>The Six Steps</h3><p>The official sequence is: <span class='keyterm'>identify the problem</span>, <span class='keyterm'>establish a theory of probable cause</span>, <span class='keyterm'>test the theory</span>, <span class='keyterm'>establish a plan of action</span>, <span class='keyterm'>implement the solution (or escalate)</span>, <span class='keyterm'>verify full system functionality</span>, and finally <span class='keyterm'>document findings, actions, and outcomes</span>. Each step has a Linux-specific flavor, and skipping straight to step five is the most common real-world mistake.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Step</th><th>Linux activity</th><th>Key tools</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1. Identify the problem</td><td>Gather symptoms, recent changes, scope; question users</td><td><code>journalctl</code>, <code>dmesg</code>, <code>last</code>, change tickets</td></tr><tr><td>2. Establish a theory</td><td>Form a hypothesis; question the obvious</td><td>logs, <code>systemctl status</code></td></tr><tr><td>3. Test the theory</td><td>Reproduce; confirm or reject the cause</td><td><code>ping</code>, <code>curl</code>, <code>ss</code>, test accounts</td></tr><tr><td>4. Plan of action</td><td>Identify steps, side effects, rollback, maintenance window</td><td>change control, backups</td></tr><tr><td>5. Implement / escalate</td><td>Apply fix or hand off; one change at a time</td><td>config edits, <code>systemctl restart</code></td></tr><tr><td>6. Verify</td><td>Confirm fix and that nothing else broke; preventive measures</td><td>functional tests, monitoring</td></tr><tr><td>7. Document</td><td>Record cause, fix, and lessons</td><td>ticketing, runbooks, wiki</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Identify the Problem</h3><p>Start by establishing the <em>scope</em>: is this one user, one host, one subnet, or the entire datacenter? A single broken login is a different problem from every login failing. Ask what changed: <span class='keyterm'>recent changes</span> are the single most common root cause. A package update, a config edit, a new firewall rule, or an expired certificate the night before is almost always the culprit. Tools like <code>rpm -qa --last</code>, <code>grep history /var/log/dnf.log</code>, or examining <code>~/.bash_history</code> reveal what was touched. Question users directly but skeptically, because they often omit the change that broke things or describe a symptom rather than the action that produced it.</p><h3>Establish and Test a Theory</h3><p>Form one hypothesis at a time and test it cheaply before committing. If you suspect DNS, run <code>dig example.com</code> before editing <code>/etc/resolv.conf</code>. If the theory is confirmed, proceed; if not, establish a new theory or escalate. The cardinal rule is to <strong>change only one thing at a time</strong> so that when the symptom changes you know exactly which action caused it. CompTIA explicitly tells you to <em>question the obvious</em> first: a tripped power strip, an unplugged cable, or caps-lock on a password are humbling but real.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Pitfall</th><th>Why it hurts</th><th>Discipline that prevents it</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Reboot before reading logs</td><td>Destroys volatile evidence</td><td>Read <code>journalctl -xe</code> first</td></tr><tr><td>Change several things at once</td><td>Cannot attribute the fix</td><td>One change, then re-test</td></tr><tr><td>No rollback plan</td><td>A bad fix becomes a second outage</td><td>Back up config, snapshot VM</td></tr><tr><td>Skip documentation</td><td>Next engineer repeats the work</td><td>One-line ticket note</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Implement, Verify, Document</h3><p>Before implementing, plan for rollback: snapshot the VM, back up the config file with <code>cp sshd_config sshd_config.bak</code>, and know how to undo. After implementing, verify not only that the original symptom is gone but that you introduced no regression, then add preventive measures such as a monitoring alert. Documentation closes the loop: a one-line ticket note saying 'certificate expired, renewed via certbot, added 30-day expiry alert' saves the next engineer hours. Escalation is a legitimate step five outcome, not a failure when the fix exceeds your access or risk authority, hand off with the evidence you have already gathered.</p><h3>Gathering Evidence Before You Touch Anything</h3><p>The identify and theory steps live or die on the quality of evidence you collect, and Linux gives you a rich toolkit for reconstructing what happened. Begin with the journal: <code>journalctl --since '1 hour ago' -p err</code> surfaces every error-level message in the recent window, and adding <code>-b</code> scopes it to the current boot so you are not misled by yesterday's noise. Correlate that against who was logged in and what they ran: <code>last</code> shows recent logins, <code>who</code> shows current sessions, and <code>journalctl _COMM=sudo</code> reveals privileged commands. On the package side, <code>rpm -qa --last</code> or <code>grep -i installed /var/log/dnf.log</code> dates every recent install so a 3 a.m. update that coincides with the outage is impossible to miss. The discipline of building a timeline questioning the obvious, confirming exactly what changed and when, and proving scope before forming a theory is what separates a methodical engineer from one who flails. When you finally write the ticket, that timeline becomes the documentation, and the same evidence trail lets you justify the rollback or escalation you chose. CompTIA tests this ordering relentlessly: the right answer is rarely the most aggressive action and almost always the one that preserves and reads evidence first.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div>If a scenario asks for your <em>first</em> action after a service fails, the answer is almost always to check the logs (<code>journalctl -u service</code> or <code>systemctl status</code>), not to restart or reboot. Rebooting first destroys evidence and is the classic wrong answer. The second-most-tested principle is changing only one variable at a time.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[5].push(
  {heading:"Monitoring Concepts: SLA, SLI, SLO, and Data Sources", body:"<p>You cannot troubleshoot what you cannot see. Monitoring is the discipline of continuously collecting data about a system so that failures are detected early and root cause is provable after the fact. The exam frames monitoring around three service-level abbreviations and the mechanisms used to acquire data from hosts. Knowing how the abbreviations nest, and which acquisition method fits a given constraint, is the testable core.</p><h3>SLA, SLO, and SLI</h3><p>A <span class='keyterm'>Service Level Agreement (SLA)</span> is the contractual promise made to customers, typically expressed as an availability percentage with financial penalties if breached, for example '99.9 percent uptime per month.' A <span class='keyterm'>Service Level Objective (SLO)</span> is the internal target the team aims for, usually set stricter than the SLA to leave a safety margin (engineering for 99.95 percent so the 99.9 percent SLA is comfortably met). A <span class='keyterm'>Service Level Indicator (SLI)</span> is the actual measured metric that feeds the objective, such as the percentage of HTTP requests returning under 200 ms or the fraction of successful responses.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Term</th><th>Meaning</th><th>Example</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>SLA</td><td>Contractual promise to the customer (with penalties)</td><td>99.9% uptime / month</td></tr><tr><td>SLO</td><td>Internal target, usually stricter than the SLA</td><td>99.95% uptime</td></tr><tr><td>SLI</td><td>The real measured metric feeding the SLO</td><td>% requests &lt; 200 ms</td></tr></tbody></table><p>The relationship is a hierarchy: the SLI is what you measure, the SLO is what you aim for, and the SLA is what you owe. The gap between the SLO and 100 percent is your <span class='keyterm'>error budget</span> the amount of failure you are permitted to spend on risky deployments before you must freeze changes. A 99.9 percent monthly SLA permits roughly 43 minutes of downtime per month; 99.99 permits about 4.3 minutes, which is why each added nine is dramatically more expensive to engineer.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Availability</th><th>Downtime / month</th><th>Downtime / year</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>99.9% (three nines)</td><td>~43 min</td><td>~8.8 hr</td></tr><tr><td>99.99% (four nines)</td><td>~4.3 min</td><td>~52 min</td></tr><tr><td>99.999% (five nines)</td><td>~26 sec</td><td>~5.3 min</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Data Acquisition: SNMP and Traps</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>SNMP</span> (Simple Network Management Protocol) is the classic mechanism for polling devices. A central manager queries each host's <span class='keyterm'>agent</span> for values from its MIB (Management Information Base) on UDP 161. Conversely, an <span class='keyterm'>SNMP trap</span> is unsolicited: the agent pushes an alert to the manager on UDP 162 the instant something crosses a threshold, so you learn of a failure immediately rather than waiting for the next poll. Always use SNMPv3 for its authentication and encryption; v1 and v2c send community strings in clear text and are trivially sniffed.</p><h3>Agent versus Agentless, Webhooks, and Aggregation</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Agent-based</span> monitoring installs software on each host (node_exporter, Telegraf, the Zabbix agent) that collects rich, local metrics and pushes or exposes them. <span class='keyterm'>Agentless</span> monitoring reaches in over existing protocols SSH, SNMP, or an HTTP API requiring nothing installed but offering shallower data. <span class='keyterm'>Webhooks</span> are HTTP callbacks: when an event fires, the monitoring system POSTs a JSON payload to a URL, integrating with chat, ticketing, or automation. <span class='keyterm'>Log aggregation</span> ships logs from every host to a central store (the ELK/Elastic stack, Loki, Graylog, or a rsyslog server) so you can search across the whole fleet from one place rather than SSHing into dozens of machines.</p><h3>Choosing an Acquisition Method</h3><p>The exam expects you to match a constraint to the right collection model rather than memorize product names. When you control the host and need deep, custom metrics application-level counters, JVM heap, per-queue depth an agent is the only realistic option because it runs inside the box and can read whatever the application exposes. When you must monitor appliances or locked-down devices where installing software is impossible (a switch, a storage array, a vendor box under support contract), agentless polling over SNMP or an HTTP API is the answer. Webhooks shine when you want event-driven integration without writing a poller at all: configure the upstream system to POST to your collector the instant something happens, trading a steady polling load for instant, push-based delivery. Log aggregation underpins all of it, because metrics tell you <em>that</em> something broke while logs tell you <em>why</em>; centralizing them means a single query across the fleet replaces dozens of SSH sessions during an incident. A common production design layers all four: agents for rich host metrics, agentless SNMP for network gear, webhooks for deploy and alert events, and a central log store such as Loki or Elasticsearch tying the timeline together so any single failure leaves a searchable trail.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Approach</th><th>Pros</th><th>Cons</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Agent-based</td><td>Deep metrics, custom data, push model</td><td>Software to deploy and maintain</td></tr><tr><td>Agentless</td><td>Nothing to install, fast rollout</td><td>Shallower data, credential management</td></tr><tr><td>SNMP poll (161)</td><td>Reliable, scheduled, widely supported</td><td>Lags between intervals</td></tr><tr><td>SNMP trap (162)</td><td>Instant on threshold breach</td><td>Best-effort UDP can be lost</td></tr></tbody></table><div class='callout'><div class='lbl'>Remember</div>An SNMP <strong>trap</strong> is pushed by the agent the moment a threshold is crossed (UDP 162); a <strong>poll</strong> is pulled by the manager on a schedule (UDP 161). Traps detect failures faster but can be lost; polling is reliable but lags. Mature setups use both: traps for speed, polling as the safety net.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[5].push(
  {heading:"Configuring Monitoring: Thresholds, Alerts, and Logging", body:"<p>Collecting data is useless without rules that decide when a human should be woken up. Configuring monitoring means defining baselines, setting thresholds, wiring up alerts, and ensuring the logging pipeline that feeds it all is reliable. Get the thresholds wrong and you either miss real outages or drown the team in noise until they ignore the pager entirely a failure mode called alert fatigue. The exam tests the relationship between a baseline, a threshold, and the alert it fires.</p><h3>Baselining</h3><p>A <span class='keyterm'>baseline</span> is the known-good profile of a healthy system: typical CPU load, memory use, disk I/O, and network throughput across daily and weekly cycles. You cannot define a meaningful threshold without one, because 'CPU at 70 percent' is alarming on an idle file server but normal on a busy database. Capture baselines over at least a full business week using historical graphing (Prometheus plus Grafana, or sar from the sysstat package) so seasonal peaks like Monday-morning logins are visible. Troubleshooting then becomes a comparison: what does this metric look like now versus its baseline?</p><h3>Thresholds and Alerts</h3><p>A <span class='keyterm'>threshold</span> is the value that triggers an alert. Good practice uses two tiers: a <em>warning</em> threshold that creates a ticket (disk at 80 percent) and a <em>critical</em> threshold that pages someone (disk at 95 percent). Thresholds should be paired with a duration to suppress transient spikes for example, fire only if CPU stays above 90 percent for five minutes so a brief backup job does not trigger a 3 a.m. page. Alerts should route by severity: warnings to a chat channel, criticals to the on-call pager.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Metric</th><th>Warning</th><th>Critical</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Root filesystem use</td><td>80%</td><td>95%</td></tr><tr><td>Load average (per core)</td><td>1.0</td><td>2.0</td></tr><tr><td>Memory available</td><td>&lt; 15%</td><td>&lt; 5%</td></tr><tr><td>5xx error rate</td><td>1%</td><td>5%</td></tr><tr><td>Inode usage</td><td>80%</td><td>95%</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Logging Configuration</h3><p>The systemd journal is configured in <code>/etc/systemd/journald.conf</code>. Key directives are <code>Storage=persistent</code> (write the journal to <code>/var/log/journal</code> so it survives reboot rather than living only in volatile <code>/run</code>), <code>SystemMaxUse=2G</code> (cap disk consumption), and <code>MaxRetentionSec=</code> (age out old entries). For classic syslog, <code>/etc/rsyslog.conf</code> and drop-ins under <code>/etc/rsyslog.d/</code> route facilities and priorities to files or to a remote collector. A line such as <code>*.* @@logserver:514</code> forwards every message over TCP to a central aggregator (a single <code>@</code> is UDP, double <code>@@</code> is TCP). Always confirm a forwarder is actually shipping with <code>logger 'test'</code> on the client and a tail on the server.</p><table><thead><tr><th>journald.conf directive</th><th>Effect</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>Storage=persistent</code></td><td>Journal survives reboot in <code>/var/log/journal</code></td></tr><tr><td><code>SystemMaxUse=2G</code></td><td>Cap total journal disk usage</td></tr><tr><td><code>MaxRetentionSec=1month</code></td><td>Age out entries older than the limit</td></tr><tr><td><code>ForwardToSyslog=yes</code></td><td>Relay journal entries to rsyslog</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Data Sources for Monitoring</h3><p>Monitoring agents read from the same kernel interfaces you use by hand: <code>/proc</code> for CPU, memory, and load; <code>/sys</code> for hardware and thermal data; the journal and <code>/var/log</code> for events; and tools like <code>sar</code> for historical sampling. Enable historical collection with <code>systemctl enable --now sysstat</code> so that after an incident you can run <code>sar -u -f /var/log/sa/sa15</code> and see exactly what the CPU was doing at 2 a.m. last night. Without that history, post-incident analysis is reduced to guesswork.</p><h3>Avoiding Alert Fatigue</h3><p>The hardest part of configuring monitoring is not collecting data but deciding what deserves a human's attention at 3 a.m. Every alert that fires and turns out to be noise erodes trust in the system until the on-call engineer mutes the pager and a real outage slips through. Three techniques fight this. First, pair every threshold with a <em>duration</em> so transient spikes are ignored: 'CPU above 90 percent for five minutes' will not fire for a one-minute backup burst. Second, use <em>two tiers</em> consistently warnings create a ticket for business hours, criticals page someone now so the volume of pages stays low and meaningful. Third, build alerts on top of baselines rather than static numbers, because a static '80 percent CPU' rule is wrong for both an idle file server and a database that runs hot by design. Tools such as Prometheus Alertmanager add <em>grouping</em>, <em>inhibition</em>, and <em>silences</em>: a single failed switch should produce one alert about the switch, not fifty alerts about every host behind it. Test alert routing the same way you test the log forwarder fire a synthetic alert and confirm it reaches the right channel before you rely on it during a real incident, because an alert that never arrives is worse than no monitoring at all.</p><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div>The team complains the journal is empty after every reboot, so post-crash investigation is impossible. The fix is to set <code>Storage=persistent</code> in <code>/etc/systemd/journald.conf</code>, create <code>/var/log/journal</code>, and restart <code>systemd-journald</code> now boot logs survive across restarts and the next crash leaves a trail readable with <code>journalctl -b -1</code>.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[5].push(
  {heading:"Diagnosing Boot Failures: GRUB, initramfs, and fstab", body:"<p>A machine that will not boot is the most intimidating failure because none of your usual tools are available. The cure is to understand exactly where in the boot chain the system stalls firmware, GRUB, kernel, initramfs, or the mounting of <code>/etc/fstab</code> and to know the recovery technique for each stage. The boot order is fixed, so the stage at which it stalls tells you which tool to reach for.</p><h3>GRUB Rescue and Editing the Kernel Command Line</h3><p>If GRUB cannot find its configuration or modules it drops to a <code>grub rescue&gt;</code> prompt. You manually point it at the boot partition with <code>set prefix=(hd0,1)/boot/grub</code>, <code>set root=(hd0,1)</code>, <code>insmod normal</code>, and <code>normal</code> to reach the menu. More commonly the menu loads but the system fails later; press <code>e</code> on the menu entry to edit the kernel command line for one boot. Useful one-shot parameters include <code>single</code> or <code>1</code> for single-user mode, <code>systemd.unit=rescue.target</code>, <code>nomodeset</code> to bypass a broken GPU driver, and <code>init=/bin/bash</code> to drop straight to a root shell bypassing systemd entirely (mount the root read-write afterward with <code>mount -o remount,rw /</code>).</p><table><thead><tr><th>Symptom</th><th>Likely stage</th><th>Recovery</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>grub rescue&gt;</code> prompt</td><td>GRUB cannot read config</td><td>set prefix/root, insmod normal</td></tr><tr><td>Kernel panic, no init</td><td>initramfs missing driver</td><td>regenerate initramfs from rescue</td></tr><tr><td>Drops to emergency shell</td><td>bad /etc/fstab entry</td><td>remount rw, fix fstab</td></tr><tr><td>Boots to wrong UI</td><td>default target wrong</td><td><code>systemctl set-default</code></td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Rebuilding grub.cfg and Regenerating initramfs</h3><p>You never hand-edit <code>grub.cfg</code>. After kernel or config changes, regenerate it with <code>grub2-mkconfig -o /boot/grub2/grub.cfg</code> on Red Hat or <code>update-grub</code> on Debian. If GRUB itself was wiped (a Windows reinstall, a botched disk), reinstall it with <code>grub2-install /dev/sda</code> (BIOS) after chrooting from rescue media. The <span class='keyterm'>initramfs</span> supplies the storage and filesystem drivers needed to reach the real root; if it is missing the right module (LVM, RAID, NVMe, encryption), the kernel panics with 'unable to mount root.' Rebuild it with <code>dracut --force --kver $(uname -r)</code> on Red Hat, <code>update-initramfs -u</code> on Debian, or <code>mkinitcpio -P</code> on Arch.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Distro family</th><th>Regenerate grub.cfg</th><th>Rebuild initramfs</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Red Hat / Fedora</td><td><code>grub2-mkconfig -o ...</code></td><td><code>dracut --force</code></td></tr><tr><td>Debian / Ubuntu</td><td><code>update-grub</code></td><td><code>update-initramfs -u</code></td></tr><tr><td>Arch</td><td><code>grub-mkconfig -o ...</code></td><td><code>mkinitcpio -P</code></td></tr></tbody></table><h3>A Bad fstab Drops You to Emergency Mode</h3><p>The most common boot failure an administrator causes is a broken <code>/etc/fstab</code>. A wrong UUID, a typo in a mount option, or a device that no longer exists makes the mount fail, and systemd drops the system to <span class='keyterm'>emergency.target</span> with a root login prompt. The root filesystem is mounted read-only, so first run <code>mount -o remount,rw /</code>, then edit <code>/etc/fstab</code> to fix or comment out the offending line, and reboot. A safe habit when adding entries is the <code>nofail</code> option, which lets the boot continue even if that filesystem is absent. Always test a new fstab line immediately with <code>mount -a</code> before rebooting.</p><h3>Boot Targets</h3><p>Systemd <span class='keyterm'>targets</span> replace SysV runlevels. <code>multi-user.target</code> is full text-mode networking (the server default), <code>graphical.target</code> adds the GUI, <code>rescue.target</code> is single-user with the root filesystem mounted, and <code>emergency.target</code> is the most minimal shell with almost nothing started. Set the persistent default with <code>systemctl set-default multi-user.target</code>, and select one for a single boot from the GRUB line with <code>systemd.unit=rescue.target</code>.</p><h3>Chroot Repair From Rescue Media</h3><p>The most powerful boot-recovery technique is the <span class='keyterm'>chroot</span>, which lets a rescue environment behave as if it were the installed system so you can run its own tools against its own disks. Boot the installation media in rescue mode (or any live ISO), then mount the real root and its supporting filesystems and pivot into them. The canonical sequence is <code>mount /dev/sda2 /mnt</code>, then bind-mount the kernel interfaces with <code>mount --bind /dev /mnt/dev</code>, <code>mount --bind /proc /mnt/proc</code>, and <code>mount --bind /sys /mnt/sys</code>, and finally <code>chroot /mnt</code>. From inside the chroot you can regenerate GRUB, rebuild the initramfs, reinstall the bootloader to the disk, reset a forgotten root password with <code>passwd</code>, or fix the broken <code>/etc/fstab</code> all using the installed system's exact kernel version and configuration rather than the live media's. This matters because <code>dracut --kver</code> and <code>grub2-install</code> must target the real system's paths to be correct. When you are done, exit the chroot, unmount in reverse order, and reboot. Knowing the chroot dance turns an unbootable machine from a reinstall into a ten-minute repair, and the exam frequently presents it as the right answer when the root filesystem is intact but the boot path is broken.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div>'Unable to mount root filesystem' right after a kernel update points to a missing driver in the initramfs regenerate it. A drop to <em>emergency mode</em> after editing storage points to a bad <code>/etc/fstab</code> remount root read-write and fix the file. Knowing which is which is a frequent exam distinction.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[5].push(
  {heading:"Kernel Panics and Driver Issues", body:"<p>A <span class='keyterm'>kernel panic</span> is the kernel's equivalent of a fatal crash: it has detected a condition from which it cannot safely continue, prints a diagnostic trace, and halts. Unlike an application crash, a panic takes the whole machine down. Diagnosing one means reading the trace, identifying the offending module or hardware, and recovering safely usually by booting a known-good kernel.</p><h3>Causes and Reading the Trace</h3><p>Common triggers are a corrupt or incompatible kernel module, failing RAM, a missing root device, a buggy driver dereferencing a null pointer, or filesystem corruption on the root device. The panic output ends with a <span class='keyterm'>call trace</span> a stack of function names leading to the fault. The line beginning <code>RIP:</code> names the instruction pointer where it died, and the trace below lists the call path. A name like <code>nouveau_</code> or <code>e1000e_</code> in the trace immediately implicates that driver. The tell-tale final lines are <code>Kernel panic - not syncing:</code> followed by the reason, such as <code>VFS: Unable to mount root fs on unknown-block(0,0)</code>, which means the root device or its driver is missing.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Panic message fragment</th><th>Likely cause</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Unable to mount root fs</td><td>Missing storage driver in initramfs / wrong root=</td></tr><tr><td>BUG: unable to handle kernel NULL pointer</td><td>Buggy driver dereferencing null</td></tr><tr><td>Machine check exception</td><td>Hardware fault (CPU, RAM)</td></tr><tr><td>attempted to kill init</td><td>PID 1 died / corrupt init</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Missing or Disabled Drivers</h3><p>If hardware is not recognized a NIC absent, a disk invisible the driver module is likely not loaded, not built, or blacklisted. Confirm what is loaded with <code>lsmod</code>, learn about a module with <code>modinfo e1000e</code>, and load it with <code>modprobe e1000e</code>. To block a buggy driver, add <code>blacklist nouveau</code> to a file in <code>/etc/modprobe.d/</code> and regenerate the initramfs; remember that blacklisting alone fails if the module is baked into an old initramfs. Module parameters can be passed persistently with an <code>options &lt;module&gt; key=value</code> line in the same directory.</p><h3>dmesg and lsmod for Live Diagnosis</h3><p>The kernel ring buffer is the first stop for any hardware or driver oddity. <code>dmesg -T --level=err,warn</code> shows timestamped errors; <code>dmesg -w</code> follows new messages live while you plug in a device. After a non-fatal kernel issue, <code>journalctl -k -b -1</code> reads the kernel messages from the <em>previous</em> boot, which is how you read a panic that did not survive on screen if the journal was persistent.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Command</th><th>Purpose</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>dmesg -T</code></td><td>Kernel ring buffer with readable timestamps</td></tr><tr><td><code>lsmod</code></td><td>Currently loaded modules</td></tr><tr><td><code>modinfo &lt;mod&gt;</code></td><td>Module details, params, dependencies</td></tr><tr><td><code>journalctl -k -b -1</code></td><td>Kernel log from the previous boot</td></tr><tr><td><code>modprobe -r &lt;mod&gt;</code></td><td>Unload a misbehaving module</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Recovery</h3><p>If a new kernel panics, boot the <em>previous</em> kernel from the GRUB 'Advanced options' submenu earlier kernels are retained for exactly this reason. From there you can rebuild the initramfs, fix the driver, or downgrade. To capture panics for later analysis on production systems, configure <span class='keyterm'>kdump</span>, which boots a tiny crash kernel that dumps memory to <code>/var/crash</code> so you can analyze the vmcore. Persistent recurring panics with <code>Machine check exception</code> point at failing hardware test RAM with memtest86 and reseat or replace components.</p><h3>Tainted Kernels and Module Signing</h3><p>When you read a panic trace, check whether the kernel is <span class='keyterm'>tainted</span> a flag the kernel sets when something has happened that makes the bug report less trustworthy, such as a proprietary driver being loaded, a module being force-loaded, or hardware reporting an error. The taint state appears in the panic output and in <code>cat /proc/sys/kernel/tainted</code> as a bitmask; a non-zero value tells you an out-of-tree or unsigned module is in play, which is frequently the real cause of an otherwise mysterious crash. Proprietary GPU drivers (NVIDIA), out-of-tree storage modules, and DKMS-built drivers that fall out of sync with a kernel update are the usual offenders. On systems with Secure Boot, the kernel additionally refuses to load unsigned modules outright, producing 'Required key not available' or a flat <code>modprobe</code> failure rather than a panic the fix there is to sign the module with the machine owner key (MOK) or disable Secure Boot for testing. When triaging, note the offending module name from the trace, confirm whether it is in-tree with <code>modinfo</code> (look at the <code>filename</code> and <code>signer</code> fields), and decide whether to blacklist it, rebuild it against the running kernel, or roll back to the previous kernel where it last worked. A tainted flag plus a third-party driver name in the trace is a near-certain diagnosis.</p><div class='callout'><div class='lbl'>Remember</div>When a freshly installed kernel panics, do not despair: reboot, choose the previous kernel under GRUB's <em>Advanced options</em>, and the working system returns. Then diagnose the new kernel's initramfs or driver from the safety of the old one. A <code>Machine check exception</code> almost always means hardware, not software.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[5].push(
  {heading:"Storage Troubleshooting: Full Filesystems, Mount Failures, and Quotas", body:"<p>Storage problems range from the mundane (a full disk) to the frightening (an unmountable root). The exam tests whether you can find what is consuming space, recover a corrupt filesystem, deal with a read-only remount, and enforce quotas before users fill the disk in the first place. The defining skill is matching the error message to the right diagnostic command.</p><h3>Finding Usage with df and du</h3><p><code>df -h</code> shows usage per mounted filesystem and is your first command when something reports 'No space left on device.' Once you know which filesystem is full, <code>du -sh /var/* | sort -h</code> drills down to find the largest consumers. A classic gotcha: <code>df</code> reports the disk full but <code>du</code> shows little usage this means a deleted file is still held open by a running process. Find it with <code>lsof +L1</code> (files with a link count of zero) and free the space by restarting the holding process or truncating the file.</p><h3>Inode Exhaustion</h3><p>A filesystem can be 'full' with plenty of free bytes if it has run out of <span class='keyterm'>inodes</span> one per file, fixed at creation time. Millions of tiny files (a runaway mail queue or session-cache directory) exhaust them. Detect this with <code>df -i</code>, which shows inode usage at 100 percent while <code>df -h</code> shows free space. The fix is to delete the small files; you cannot add inodes without recreating the filesystem (XFS allocates inodes dynamically and is far less prone to this).</p><table><thead><tr><th>Command</th><th>What it reveals</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>df -h</code></td><td>Space used per filesystem</td></tr><tr><td><code>df -i</code></td><td>Inode usage (catches inode exhaustion)</td></tr><tr><td><code>du -sh *</code></td><td>Size of each item in a directory</td></tr><tr><td><code>lsof +L1</code></td><td>Open files that have been deleted</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Repairing Unmountable Filesystems</h3><p>A filesystem that will not mount due to corruption needs a repair tool run on the <em>unmounted</em> device never on a mounted one. For ext2/3/4 use <code>fsck /dev/sdb1</code> (which dispatches to <code>e2fsck</code>); add <code>-y</code> to answer yes to all repairs. If the primary superblock is damaged, recover from a backup with <code>e2fsck -b 32768 /dev/sdb1</code>. XFS uses its own tool: <code>xfs_repair /dev/sdb1</code>, and if the log is dirty you may need <code>xfs_repair -L</code> to zero the log (a last resort that can lose recent writes). The root filesystem cannot be unmounted while running, so repair it from rescue media or let the boot-time fsck run by touching <code>/forcefsck</code>.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Filesystem</th><th>Repair tool</th><th>Last-resort flag</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>ext2/3/4</td><td><code>fsck</code> / <code>e2fsck -y</code></td><td><code>-b 32768</code> (backup superblock)</td></tr><tr><td>XFS</td><td><code>xfs_repair</code></td><td><code>-L</code> (zero dirty log)</td></tr><tr><td>Btrfs</td><td><code>btrfs check</code></td><td><code>--repair</code> (risky)</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Read-Only Remount and OS Full</h3><p>When the kernel detects filesystem errors it often <span class='keyterm'>remounts read-only</span> to prevent further damage suddenly nothing can be written and logs stop. Confirm with <code>mount | grep ' / '</code> showing <code>ro</code>, check <code>dmesg</code> for the I/O or EXT4-fs error that triggered it, and after running a repair remount with <code>mount -o remount,rw /</code>. If the OS filesystem itself is completely full, services fail to write state and the system may become unusable; clear space first by truncating large logs with <code>truncate -s 0 /var/log/huge.log</code> or vacuuming the journal with <code>journalctl --vacuum-size=200M</code>.</p><h3>Disk Quotas</h3><p>Quotas cap how much space or how many inodes a user or group may consume. Enable them by adding <code>usrquota,grpquota</code> to the mount options in <code>/etc/fstab</code>, remounting, then running <code>quotacheck -cugm /home</code> and <code>quotaon /home</code>. Edit limits interactively with <code>edquota -u alice</code>, setting a soft limit (a warning threshold with a grace period) and a hard limit (an absolute cap). Audit with <code>repquota -a</code> for a full report or <code>quota -u alice</code> for one user.</p><h3>LVM and Mount Failures</h3><p>On systems using the Logical Volume Manager, a 'full' filesystem may simply need more space added live, and a missing volume may explain a boot-time mount failure. Confirm the layout with <code>pvs</code>, <code>vgs</code>, and <code>lvs</code>, which list physical volumes, volume groups, and logical volumes with their free space. If the volume group has unallocated extents, grow the logical volume and its filesystem online: <code>lvextend -L +5G /dev/vg0/lv_var</code> followed by <code>resize2fs /dev/vg0/lv_var</code> for ext4, or <code>xfs_growfs /var</code> for XFS (XFS can only grow, never shrink). When a mount fails entirely, the cause is usually one of a short list: a wrong UUID in <code>/etc/fstab</code> after a disk was recloned, a filesystem type mismatch, a missing kernel module for that filesystem, or an inactive logical volume. Verify the device's real UUID with <code>blkid</code> and compare it against the fstab line character by character a single transposed digit drops the boot to emergency mode. For LVM specifically, an inactive volume after a failed device must be reactivated with <code>vgchange -ay</code> before it can be mounted. Always validate a new or edited mount with <code>mount -a</code> while the system is still up, because that command replays every fstab entry and surfaces the error immediately instead of at the next reboot when you are locked out.</p><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div><code>df -h</code> says <code>/var</code> is 100 percent full, but <code>du -sh /var</code> only accounts for half of it. A rotated log was deleted while syslog still held it open. <code>lsof +L1</code> reveals the deleted file pinned by <code>rsyslogd</code>; restarting that service releases the blocks and <code>df</code> instantly drops.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[5].push(
  {heading:"systemd Unit Failures and Journal Forensics", body:"<p>On every modern Linux system, <span class='keyterm'>systemd</span> is PID 1 and the manager of all services. When a service will not start, stays dead, or restarts endlessly, systemd and its journal hold the answer. Mastering <code>systemctl</code> and <code>journalctl</code> is the single highest-leverage troubleshooting skill on the exam, and several classic 'my fix did nothing' traps live here.</p><h3>Finding Failed Units</h3><p>Start broad with <code>systemctl --failed</code>, which lists every unit in the failed state across the system one screen that tells you what is broken. Then drill into a specific unit with <code>systemctl status nginx</code>, which shows the active state, the main PID, recent log lines, and crucially the exit code and signal. An <code>Active: failed (Result: exit-code)</code> line with <code>status=1/FAILURE</code> means the program ran and exited non-zero; <code>Result: timeout</code> means it never signaled readiness; <code>Result: signal</code> means it was killed.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Command</th><th>Purpose</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>systemctl --failed</code></td><td>List all failed units</td></tr><tr><td><code>systemctl status &lt;u&gt;</code></td><td>State, PID, exit code, recent logs</td></tr><tr><td><code>journalctl -u &lt;u&gt;</code></td><td>Full log history for a unit</td></tr><tr><td><code>journalctl -xe</code></td><td>Recent entries with explanations, jump to end</td></tr><tr><td><code>systemctl daemon-reload</code></td><td>Reload unit files after editing</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Journal Forensics</h3><p>The journal is the authoritative log. <code>journalctl -u sshd --since today</code> scopes to one unit and time window; <code>journalctl -xe</code> jumps to the most recent entries with the <code>-x</code> flag adding catalog explanations of known errors. Filter by boot with <code>-b</code> (current) or <code>-b -1</code> (previous), by priority with <code>-p err</code>, and follow live with <code>-f</code>. To prove a chain of events, combine: <code>journalctl -u app.service -p warning --since '10 min ago'</code>.</p><h3>The daemon-reload Trap</h3><p>After editing a unit file in <code>/etc/systemd/system/</code> or running <code>systemctl edit</code>, systemd does <em>not</em> see the change until you run <code>systemctl daemon-reload</code>. Forgetting this produces the maddening symptom where your edit 'has no effect' and status shows the old configuration with a warning that the unit file changed on disk. Always <code>daemon-reload</code> after editing units, then restart the service.</p><h3>Dependency Failures and Masked Units</h3><p>A service may fail because something it <code>Requires=</code> failed first systemd will show 'Dependency failed for' and refuse to start it. Inspect the chain with <code>systemctl list-dependencies app.service</code>. A <span class='keyterm'>masked</span> unit is the strongest form of disable: <code>systemctl mask</code> symlinks the unit to <code>/dev/null</code> so it cannot be started by any means manual, dependency, or socket. The symptom is 'Unit is masked' on every start attempt; the fix is <code>systemctl unmask app.service</code>. This trips up administrators who masked a service months ago and forgot.</p><h3>Restart Loops</h3><p>A unit with <code>Restart=always</code> that keeps crashing enters a <span class='keyterm'>restart loop</span>. Systemd's start-limit logic eventually gives up with 'start request repeated too quickly' and the unit lands in failed state. Read <code>journalctl -u app</code> to find why each start dies often a config error or a missing dependency. After fixing, clear the rate-limit block with <code>systemctl reset-failed app.service</code> before restarting, or systemd may still refuse.</p><h3>Reading Exit Codes and Timers</h3><p>The exit code in <code>systemctl status</code> is the fastest clue to <em>why</em> a service died, and the exam expects you to interpret the common ones. <code>status=0/SUCCESS</code> with the unit inactive simply means the program finished normally a oneshot job that completed. A non-zero <code>status=N</code> is the program's own exit code: <code>status=1</code> is a generic failure, <code>status=203/EXEC</code> means systemd could not execute the binary at all (wrong path or missing execute bit in <code>ExecStart=</code>), <code>status=200/CHDIR</code> means a bad <code>WorkingDirectory=</code>, and <code>status=217/USER</code> means the <code>User=</code> account does not exist. When the line reads <code>Result: signal</code> the process was killed by a signal SIGSEGV points at a crash, SIGKILL often points at the OOM killer. Beyond plain services, systemd timers replace cron on many systems, and a job that 'did not run' may be a disabled or misconfigured timer rather than a failed service. List them with <code>systemctl list-timers --all</code>, which shows the next and last trigger time for every timer, and inspect the pair of <code>.timer</code> and <code>.service</code> units. A timer that shows no 'next' time is not enabled; a service that the timer triggers but which exits non-zero will show up in <code>systemctl --failed</code> just like any other unit, so the same forensic workflow applies.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Symptom</th><th>Cause</th><th>Fix</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Edit 'has no effect'</td><td>Unit file not reloaded</td><td><code>systemctl daemon-reload</code></td></tr><tr><td>'Unit is masked'</td><td>Masked to /dev/null</td><td><code>systemctl unmask</code></td></tr><tr><td>'start request repeated too quickly'</td><td>Hit start limit in restart loop</td><td><code>systemctl reset-failed</code></td></tr><tr><td>'Dependency failed for'</td><td>A <code>Requires=</code> unit failed</td><td>Fix the dependency first</td></tr></tbody></table><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div>Three classic 'my fix did nothing' traps: you edited a unit file but forgot <code>systemctl daemon-reload</code>; the unit is <em>masked</em> so it silently refuses to start (<code>systemctl unmask</code>); or a restart loop hit the start limit and needs <code>systemctl reset-failed</code>. Memorize all three.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[5].push(
  {heading:"Network Troubleshooting I: Link, Addressing, and Routing", body:"<p>Network problems are best attacked from the bottom of the stack upward: is the link up, does the interface have a correct address, and can packets reach the gateway and beyond. Working this order prevents wasting time on DNS when the cable is unplugged, and the exam frequently asks you to pick the correct layer to test next.</p><h3>Link Layer: Is the Interface Up?</h3><p>Start with <code>ip link show</code>. A healthy interface reads <code>state UP</code> with <code>LOWER_UP</code>; <code>NO-CARRIER</code> means no physical signal a dead cable, bad switch port, or disabled port. Bring an interface up administratively with <code>ip link set eth0 up</code>. For physical link details, <code>ethtool eth0</code> reports negotiated speed, duplex, and whether 'Link detected: yes.' A mismatch such as half-duplex on one side causes massive packet loss under load. Check the driver and ring buffers here too with <code>ethtool -i eth0</code> and <code>ethtool -S eth0</code> for error counters.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Symptom</th><th>Command</th><th>Meaning</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>NO-CARRIER</code></td><td><code>ip link</code></td><td>Physical link down (cable/port)</td></tr><tr><td>Link detected: no</td><td><code>ethtool eth0</code></td><td>No carrier at the NIC</td></tr><tr><td>No IPv4 address</td><td><code>ip addr</code></td><td>DHCP failed or static missing</td></tr><tr><td>No default route</td><td><code>ip route</code></td><td>Gateway unset can't leave subnet</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Addressing: IP, Subnet, MTU, and MAC</h3><p><code>ip addr show</code> reveals whether the interface has an IPv4 address and what subnet mask. A missing address means DHCP failed or the static config is wrong; a <code>169.254.x.x</code> address is APIPA, the link-local fallback that proves DHCP got no answer. A wrong <span class='keyterm'>subnet mask</span> makes the host think remote addresses are local, so it ARPs for them instead of routing reachability breaks silently for off-subnet hosts. <span class='keyterm'>MTU</span> mismatches cause large packets to be dropped while ping works: set and test with <code>ip link set eth0 mtu 9000</code> and <code>ping -M do -s 8972 host</code>. A duplicate <span class='keyterm'>MAC address</span> on the segment causes intermittent connectivity as the switch's MAC table flaps; check with <code>ip link</code> and <code>arp -n</code>.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Clue</th><th>Diagnosis</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>169.254.x.x</code> address</td><td>APIPA DHCP got no answer</td></tr><tr><td>Wrong subnet mask</td><td>Off-subnet hosts unreachable, host ARPs instead of routes</td></tr><tr><td>Ping works, big transfers stall</td><td>MTU mismatch / fragmentation</td></tr><tr><td>Intermittent drops on a segment</td><td>Duplicate MAC, switch table flapping</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Routing and the Default Gateway</h3><p><code>ip route show</code> lists the routing table; the <code>default via 192.168.1.1 dev eth0</code> line is the gateway. Without a default route you can reach your own subnet but nothing beyond it the symptom is 'can ping local hosts, cannot ping the internet.' Add one with <code>ip route add default via 192.168.1.1</code>. Trace where packets die with <code>traceroute 8.8.8.8</code> or <code>mtr</code>, which shows the hop at which responses stop.</p><h3>Cannot Ping the Server</h3><p>When you cannot ping a server, isolate the layer methodically: ping your own gateway first (rules out local link and routing), then ping the remote host by IP (rules out DNS), then by name. If IP works but name fails, the problem is DNS, not the network covered next. If the gateway itself does not answer, the problem is local: link down, wrong IP, wrong mask, or no route. Remember that many hosts and firewalls drop ICMP, so a failed ping does not always mean the host is down confirm with a TCP check like <code>nc -vz host 443</code>.</p><h3>Persistent Configuration and NetworkManager</h3><p>A fix applied with <code>ip</code> commands evaporates at the next reboot because the <code>ip</code> tool changes only the running kernel state, not the on-disk configuration. This is a classic trap: you add an address or a route, connectivity returns, you move on, and the problem recurs after a restart. To make a change survive, edit the host's persistence layer most modern distributions use <span class='keyterm'>NetworkManager</span>, configured through <code>nmcli</code>. Inspect connections with <code>nmcli connection show</code>, change a setting with <code>nmcli con mod 'eth0' ipv4.addresses 192.168.1.50/24 ipv4.gateway 192.168.1.1 ipv4.method manual</code>, and apply it with <code>nmcli con up 'eth0'</code>. Older or server-minimal systems may use <code>systemd-networkd</code> files under <code>/etc/systemd/network/</code> or distribution-specific files such as <code>/etc/sysconfig/network-scripts/ifcfg-eth0</code> on older Red Hat or Netplan YAML on Ubuntu. When troubleshooting, always confirm which manager actually owns the interface, because editing the wrong file changes nothing and editing two of them creates a fight where one tool reverts the other. The general workflow is: prove the fix works with a temporary <code>ip</code> command, then commit it to whichever persistence tool is authoritative, then reboot once to confirm it sticks.</p><div class='callout'><div class='lbl'>Remember</div>The order is link, address, gateway, beyond. An address of <code>169.254.x.x</code> is the dead giveaway that DHCP failed the host self-assigned APIPA. 'Local works, internet doesn't' almost always means a missing or wrong default route. A failed ping alone never proves a host is down ICMP is often filtered.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[5].push(
  {heading:"Network Troubleshooting II: DNS, DHCP, and Firewalls", body:"<p>Once the link and routing are proven good, name resolution, address assignment, and firewall rules are the usual suspects. 'It's always DNS' is a sysadmin proverb for good reason resolution failures masquerade as application bugs constantly, and the exam loves to test the difference between a refused connection and a filtered one.</p><h3>Diagnosing DNS Failures</h3><p>Test resolution directly with <code>dig example.com</code> or <code>nslookup example.com</code>. A <code>status: NOERROR</code> with an answer section means DNS works; <code>status: NXDOMAIN</code> means the name does not exist; a timeout means the resolver is unreachable. Crucially, <code>dig @8.8.8.8 example.com</code> queries a specific server if that works but plain <code>dig</code> does not, your configured resolver is the problem. The configured resolvers live in <code>/etc/resolv.conf</code> (often a symlink managed by systemd-resolved or NetworkManager). The order in which name sources are consulted files versus DNS is set in <code>/etc/nsswitch.conf</code> on the <code>hosts:</code> line; a stale or wrong <code>/etc/hosts</code> entry there overrides DNS and causes a host to resolve to the wrong IP.</p><table><thead><tr><th>dig result</th><th>Meaning</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>NOERROR + answer</td><td>Resolution working</td></tr><tr><td>NXDOMAIN</td><td>Name does not exist</td></tr><tr><td>connection timed out</td><td>Resolver unreachable / wrong resolv.conf</td></tr><tr><td>SERVFAIL</td><td>Resolver error (often DNSSEC or upstream)</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>DHCP Issues</h3><p>If a host has no address or an APIPA <code>169.254</code> address, DHCP failed. Renew the lease manually with <code>dhclient -r eth0 &amp;&amp; dhclient eth0</code> (or the NetworkManager equivalent) and watch <code>journalctl -u NetworkManager -f</code> for the DHCPDISCOVER/OFFER/REQUEST/ACK exchange. No OFFER means the request never reached a server or the scope is exhausted check the DHCP server logs and whether a relay is needed across subnets. A wrong VLAN or an unplugged uplink also silently blocks DHCP.</p><h3>Misconfigured Firewalls</h3><p>A firewall blocking traffic produces a very specific symptom: the TCP connection hangs and eventually times out, rather than being instantly refused. Inspect the rules with <code>firewall-cmd --list-all</code> (firewalld), <code>nft list ruleset</code> (nftables), or <code>iptables -L -n -v</code>. To allow a service add it, for example <code>firewall-cmd --add-service=https --permanent &amp;&amp; firewall-cmd --reload</code>. Remember that filtering can be local (host firewall), on a network device, or in a cloud security group test from multiple vantage points to localize it.</p><h3>Port Checks: ss, nc, and nmap</h3><p>To confirm a server is actually listening, run <code>ss -tlnp</code> on the server it lists every listening TCP socket with the owning process. If the port is not listed, the service is not running or bound to the wrong interface (bound to <code>127.0.0.1</code> instead of <code>0.0.0.0</code> is a classic). From a client, test reachability with <code>nc -vz server 443</code> ('succeeded' means the port is open and reachable) or scan with <code>nmap -p 443 server</code>. A <code>refused</code> result means nothing is listening; a <code>filtered</code>/timeout result means a firewall is silently dropping the packets.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Result</th><th>Interpretation</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>succeeded</code> / open</td><td>Service listening and reachable</td></tr><tr><td>Connection refused</td><td>Reached host, nothing listening on port</td></tr><tr><td>Timeout / filtered</td><td>Firewall silently dropping packets</td></tr><tr><td>Bound to 127.0.0.1</td><td>Service up but not reachable remotely</td></tr></tbody></table><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div>Distinguish the two failure signatures: <em>Connection refused</em> means you reached the host but no service is on that port (service down or wrong bind). A <em>timeout / filtered</em> result means a firewall is dropping the packet. 'Connection refused' is not a firewall it is a missing listener.</div><h3>Capturing Packets When Logic Fails</h3><p>When the higher-level tools disagree or the failure is intermittent, drop to packet capture and watch the wire directly. <code>tcpdump -ni eth0 host 10.0.0.5 and port 443</code> shows exactly which packets leave and arrive, and the absence of an expected reply localizes the break instantly: if you see your SYN go out but no SYN-ACK return, the far side or a firewall between you is dropping it; if you see RST come back, something is actively refusing. For DNS specifically, <code>tcpdump -ni eth0 port 53</code> reveals whether the query even reaches the resolver and whether an answer returns, cutting through ambiguity about whether the problem is the client, the network, or the server. Add timing with the <code>-tttt</code> flag and write to a file with <code>-w capture.pcap</code> for later analysis in Wireshark. Two recurring gotchas deserve emphasis. First, asymmetric routing or a missing return route makes a request arrive but the reply never come back, which looks like a firewall drop but is really a routing bug on the server side prove it by capturing on both ends. Second, MTU and fragmentation problems let small packets (including ping and the TCP handshake) succeed while large transfers hang; a capture showing the connection established but stalling mid-transfer points straight at path MTU, fixable by lowering the MTU or enabling MSS clamping.</p>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[5].push(
  {heading:"Security Troubleshooting: Permissions, ACLs, and Attributes", body:"<p>'Permission denied' is one of the most frequent error messages on Linux, and it has several distinct causes: classic mode bits, a denying ACL, an immutable attribute, or wrong ownership. Diagnosing it means knowing which layer is blocking access and how to inspect each one. A key exam distinction is 'Permission denied' (mode/ACL) versus 'Operation not permitted' (attribute or capability).</p><h3>Diagnosing Permission Denied</h3><p>Start with <code>ls -l</code> on the file to read the owner, group, and the <code>rwx</code> bits. Remember that to <em>access</em> a file you also need execute (<code>x</code>) permission on every directory in its path a denial may be on a parent directory, not the file itself. The <code>namei -l /path/to/file</code> command is purpose-built for this: it walks each path component and prints the permissions and ownership at every level, instantly revealing which directory blocks you. For execution failures, confirm the file itself is executable and not mounted <code>noexec</code> (check with <code>mount | grep noexec</code>).</p><table><thead><tr><th>Layer</th><th>Inspect with</th><th>Fix with</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Mode bits</td><td><code>ls -l</code>, <code>namei -l</code></td><td><code>chmod</code></td></tr><tr><td>Ownership</td><td><code>ls -l</code>, <code>stat</code></td><td><code>chown</code> / <code>chgrp</code></td></tr><tr><td>ACL</td><td><code>getfacl</code></td><td><code>setfacl</code></td></tr><tr><td>Attributes</td><td><code>lsattr</code></td><td><code>chattr</code></td></tr></tbody></table><h3>ACL Conflicts</h3><p>When <code>ls -l</code> shows a trailing <code>+</code> on the permission string, an <span class='keyterm'>Access Control List</span> is in play and the mode bits alone do not tell the whole story. View it with <code>getfacl file</code>, which lists named user and group entries plus the <span class='keyterm'>mask</span>. The mask is the trap: it caps the effective permissions of all named entries and the group, so even if Alice has an ACL of <code>rwx</code>, a mask of <code>r--</code> reduces her effective rights to read-only (getfacl prints '#effective:r--' to warn you). Fix by widening the mask or the entry with <code>setfacl -m u:alice:rwx file</code>, then re-check.</p><h3>Immutable and Append-Only Attributes</h3><p>If even <em>root</em> cannot modify or delete a file getting 'Operation not permitted' rather than 'Permission denied' suspect a file attribute. Run <code>lsattr file</code>; an <code>i</code> flag means <span class='keyterm'>immutable</span> (cannot be changed, renamed, or deleted by anyone) and an <code>a</code> flag means append-only. Remove the immutable bit with <code>chattr -i file</code>. This is a favorite exam scenario because the file looks perfectly writable in <code>ls -l</code>, yet writes fail; the attribute is invisible to the mode-bit view.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Error text</th><th>Most likely cause</th><th>Reveal with</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Permission denied</td><td>Mode bits or ACL / parent dir lacks <code>x</code></td><td><code>namei -l</code>, <code>getfacl</code></td></tr><tr><td>Operation not permitted</td><td>Immutable/append attribute</td><td><code>lsattr</code></td></tr><tr><td>+ on the mode string</td><td>An ACL is overriding mode bits</td><td><code>getfacl</code></td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Ownership Errors and Remote Access</h3><p>Files created by the wrong process often end up owned by <code>root</code> when a user needs them, or vice versa. <code>stat file</code> shows numeric UID/GID, helping when a username does not resolve. A frequent remote-access failure is SSH refusing key auth because the user's <code>~/.ssh</code> is group- or world-writable OpenSSH deliberately rejects keys when permissions are too loose. The fix is <code>chmod 700 ~/.ssh</code> and <code>chmod 600 ~/.ssh/authorized_keys</code> with correct ownership. A whole home directory owned by root after a botched restore similarly breaks login; <code>chown -R user:user /home/user</code> repairs it.</p><h3>setuid, the Sticky Bit, and Group Collaboration</h3><p>Beyond the basic <code>rwx</code> triad, three special-permission bits cause subtle access failures the exam likes to probe. The <span class='keyterm'>setuid</span> bit (shown as <code>s</code> in the owner's execute slot) makes a program run with the file owner's identity rather than the caller's it is why <code>passwd</code>, owned by root, can edit <code>/etc/shadow</code> when an ordinary user runs it. If <code>passwd</code> or <code>sudo</code> suddenly reports a permission error, confirm the setuid bit survived a backup or <code>chmod</code> with <code>ls -l</code> (a lost bit shows plain <code>x</code>) and restore it with <code>chmod u+s</code>. The <span class='keyterm'>setgid</span> bit on a directory makes new files inherit the directory's group rather than the creator's primary group, which is the standard way to build a shared collaboration folder; without it, members of a shared group keep creating files their teammates cannot read. The <span class='keyterm'>sticky bit</span> (shown as <code>t</code>, set on <code>/tmp</code>) restricts deletion so users can only remove their own files in a world-writable directory; if users complain they can delete each other's temp files, the sticky bit is missing restore it with <code>chmod +t</code>. Diagnose all three at once with <code>stat</code> or <code>ls -l</code>, reading the leftmost permission characters carefully, because a capital <code>S</code> or <code>T</code> warns that the special bit is set but the underlying execute bit is not, a common misconfiguration.</p><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div>A user has an ACL of <code>rwx</code> on a shared file yet still gets 'Permission denied' on write. <code>getfacl</code> shows <code>mask::r--</code> and <code>#effective:r--</code> next to her entry. The mask is throttling her ACL. <code>setfacl -m m::rwx file</code> raises the mask and she can write immediately no change to her own entry was needed.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[5].push(
  {heading:"Security Troubleshooting: SELinux Denials and Repositories", body:"<p>On Red Hat-family systems, <span class='keyterm'>SELinux</span> (Security-Enhanced Linux) enforces mandatory access control on top of normal permissions. When everything looks correct yet an application is denied, SELinux is often the hidden cause. Separately, a misconfigured package repository blocks updates entirely; both are exam staples, and the wrong answer to each (disable SELinux, set gpgcheck=0) is always a trap.</p><h3>Diagnosing AVC Denials</h3><p>SELinux logs every denial as an <span class='keyterm'>AVC</span> (Access Vector Cache) message in the audit log. Find them with <code>ausearch -m AVC -ts recent</code> or <code>grep AVC /var/log/audit/audit.log</code>. Each entry names the source context, target context, and the action denied. The <code>sealert</code> tool (from setroubleshoot) translates a raw AVC into a plain-English explanation with a suggested fix: <code>sealert -a /var/log/audit/audit.log</code>. The first question is always whether the denial is SELinux check <code>getenforce</code>, which returns <code>Enforcing</code>, <code>Permissive</code>, or <code>Disabled</code>.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Command</th><th>Purpose</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>getenforce</code></td><td>Current SELinux mode</td></tr><tr><td><code>ausearch -m AVC -ts recent</code></td><td>Recent denials from the audit log</td></tr><tr><td><code>sealert -a &lt;log&gt;</code></td><td>Human-readable analysis with fixes</td></tr><tr><td><code>restorecon -Rv &lt;path&gt;</code></td><td>Reset contexts to policy default</td></tr><tr><td><code>setenforce 0</code></td><td>Switch to permissive (testing only)</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Permissive Testing and audit2allow</h3><p>To confirm SELinux is the culprit without changing policy, temporarily set <code>setenforce 0</code> (permissive). If the problem vanishes, SELinux was blocking it; if it persists, look elsewhere. <strong>Permissive is a diagnostic, not a fix</strong> never leave production in permissive or disabled. The correct fix is usually a context relabel or a boolean (toggle one with <code>setsebool -P httpd_can_network_connect on</code>). If a genuinely new access is needed, <code>audit2allow -a -M mymodule</code> reads the denials and generates a custom policy module you can load with <code>semodule -i mymodule.pp</code> but use this sparingly and only after understanding why the denial occurred.</p><h3>Contexts After Moving Files: restorecon</h3><p>The most common SELinux pitfall: you <code>mv</code> a file into <code>/var/www/html</code> and Apache gets a 403. Moving a file preserves its <em>original</em> context, whereas copying inherits the destination's context. The web server's policy expects the <code>httpd_sys_content_t</code> type, but the moved file still carries, say, <code>user_home_t</code>. Diagnose with <code>ls -Z file</code> to see the context, then fix with <code>restorecon -Rv /var/www/html</code>, which resets every file to the policy-defined default. For a permanent custom location, define the rule with <code>semanage fcontext -a -t httpd_sys_content_t '/web(/.*)?'</code> first, then <code>restorecon</code>.</p><h3>Misconfigured Package Repository</h3><p>When <code>dnf update</code> fails, the repository definition is usually at fault. Errors fall into two camps. A wrong <code>baseurl</code> or a dead mirror yields 'Cannot prepare internal mirrorlist' or 404s check the <code>.repo</code> file in <code>/etc/yum.repos.d/</code> and test the URL with <code>curl -I</code>. A <span class='keyterm'>GPG</span> failure ('Public key for package is not installed' or 'signature could not be verified') means the repository's signing key is missing or wrong; import it with <code>rpm --import &lt;keyfile&gt;</code> or fix the <code>gpgkey=</code> line. As a last-resort diagnostic you can set <code>gpgcheck=0</code>, but disabling signature verification is a security risk and not the real fix. Clear stale metadata with <code>dnf clean all</code> after correcting the file.</p><h3>Booleans, Ports, and File Contexts</h3><p>Most legitimate SELinux problems are solved not by writing policy but by flipping a built-in <span class='keyterm'>boolean</span> or registering a non-default port or path with the existing policy. Booleans are named switches the policy authors built for common needs: <code>getsebool -a | grep httpd</code> lists every Apache-related toggle, and <code>setsebool -P httpd_can_network_connect on</code> permanently allows the web server to make outbound connections (the <code>-P</code> writes it to disk so it survives reboot). This single boolean resolves a huge fraction of 'my PHP app cannot reach the database or an API' denials, and the correct exam answer is the boolean, never disabling SELinux. When a service must listen on a non-standard port say sshd on 2222 SELinux blocks the bind until you register it with <code>semanage port -a -t ssh_port_t -p tcp 2222</code>; query existing mappings with <code>semanage port -l</code>. For custom file locations, the durable fix is a two-step pattern: declare the context rule with <code>semanage fcontext -a -t httpd_sys_content_t '/srv/web(/.*)?'</code> so it persists across relabels, then apply it with <code>restorecon -Rv /srv/web</code>. The mental model to carry into the exam is a decision tree: is it a known toggle (boolean), a non-default port (semanage port), or a file in the wrong place (fcontext plus restorecon)? Reaching for <code>setenforce 0</code> as anything other than a momentary confirmation is always the wrong answer.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Repo error</th><th>Cause</th><th>Fix</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>404 / Cannot prepare mirrorlist</td><td>Bad <code>baseurl</code> or dead mirror</td><td>Correct <code>.repo</code>, test with <code>curl -I</code></td></tr><tr><td>Signature could not be verified</td><td>Missing/wrong GPG key</td><td><code>rpm --import</code>, fix <code>gpgkey=</code></td></tr><tr><td>Stale package data after fixing</td><td>Cached metadata</td><td><code>dnf clean all</code></td></tr></tbody></table><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div>A file <code>mv</code>'d into a web root that returns 403 is the canonical SELinux question: the answer is <code>restorecon</code> (because move preserves the old context), not <code>chmod</code>. And never 'fix' SELinux by disabling it use permissive only to confirm, then relabel or set the proper boolean.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[5].push(
  {heading:"Performance I: CPU, Memory, and Swapping", body:"<p>Performance complaints 'the server is slow' require turning a vague symptom into a measured bottleneck. The first division is whether the constraint is CPU, memory, disk, or network. This section covers CPU saturation, memory exhaustion, and the swapping that ties them together; disk and I/O follow next. The exam wants you to read <code>top</code>, <code>free</code>, and <code>vmstat</code> output and name the true bottleneck.</p><h3>High CPU and Load Average</h3><p><code>top</code> (or the friendlier <code>htop</code>) is the starting point, sorting processes by CPU. The <span class='keyterm'>load average</span> three numbers for the 1, 5, and 15-minute windows is the count of processes running or waiting to run. The rule of thumb: divide load by core count; a load of 8 on 8 cores (1.0 per core) is fully busy but not overloaded, while a load of 16 on 8 cores means processes are queuing. Distinguish the kind of load using <code>top</code>'s CPU line: high <code>%us</code> is userspace computation, high <code>%sy</code> is kernel/system calls, and high <code>%wa</code> is I/O wait the CPU is idle waiting on disk, which is really a storage problem. <code>mpstat -P ALL 1</code> breaks usage out per core, revealing whether a single-threaded process is pinning one core while others idle.</p><table><thead><tr><th>top metric</th><th>Meaning</th><th>Implication</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>%us high</td><td>User CPU</td><td>Application compute-bound</td></tr><tr><td>%sy high</td><td>System/kernel CPU</td><td>Syscall-heavy / driver issue</td></tr><tr><td>%wa high</td><td>I/O wait</td><td>Disk is the bottleneck, not CPU</td></tr><tr><td>%st high</td><td>Steal time</td><td>Noisy-neighbor VM / overcommitted host</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Memory Exhaustion and the OOM Killer</h3><p>Read memory with <code>free -h</code>. The number that matters is <span class='keyterm'>available</span>, not 'free' Linux deliberately uses spare RAM for the page cache, so low 'free' is healthy; low 'available' is the warning sign. When memory truly runs out and swap is exhausted, the kernel invokes the <span class='keyterm'>OOM killer</span>, which terminates the process with the highest <code>oom_score</code> to save the system. The fingerprint is a process vanishing with no application error; confirm with <code>dmesg | grep -i 'killed process'</code> or <code>journalctl -k | grep oom</code>, which names the victim and how much memory was in use. Tune which processes are spared with <code>oom_score_adj</code>.</p><h3>Swapping and the si/so Columns</h3><p>Some swap use is normal; <em>active</em> swapping (thrashing) is the killer. <code>vmstat 1</code> shows two decisive columns under <code>swap</code>: <code>si</code> (swap-in) and <code>so</code> (swap-out) in KB/s. Sustained non-zero <code>si</code>/<code>so</code> means the system is constantly paging memory to and from disk, and performance collapses because disk is thousands of times slower than RAM. The fix is to add RAM, reduce memory demand, or for latency-sensitive systems lower <code>vm.swappiness</code> so the kernel prefers reclaiming cache over swapping application memory.</p><table><thead><tr><th>vmstat column</th><th>Healthy</th><th>Problem</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>si</code> / <code>so</code></td><td>0 (or brief)</td><td>Sustained &gt; 0 = thrashing</td></tr><tr><td><code>r</code> (run queue)</td><td>&le; cores</td><td>&gt; cores = CPU contention</td></tr><tr><td><code>b</code> (blocked)</td><td>~0</td><td>Processes stuck on I/O</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>High Latency and Slow Response</h3><p>If CPU, memory, and swap all look healthy yet the application is slow, the bottleneck is elsewhere disk I/O (next section), network round-trips, a saturated database, or lock contention. Correlate the slow period with metrics using <code>sar</code> history, and check whether load spiked at a known time (a cron job, a backup). A single runaway process found in <code>top</code> can be traced with <code>strace -p PID</code> to see what syscall it is stuck on, or profiled with <code>perf top</code> to find the hot function.</p><h3>Zombies, Runaways, and Process Triage</h3><p>Not every CPU or memory complaint is a capacity problem; sometimes a single misbehaving process is the whole story, and the exam expects you to identify and act on it. In <code>top</code>, sort by CPU (<code>P</code>) or memory (<code>M</code>) and read the offender's state in the <code>S</code> column: <code>R</code> is running, <code>S</code> is sleeping, <code>D</code> is uninterruptible sleep (stuck in a kernel I/O wait and a frequent cause of rising load that no amount of CPU explains), and <code>Z</code> is a <span class='keyterm'>zombie</span>. A zombie is a finished child whose parent never reaped its exit status; zombies consume no CPU or memory but occupy a process-table slot, and a flood of them points at a buggy parent that is not calling <code>wait()</code>. You cannot kill a zombie directly it is already dead so the fix is to signal or restart its parent, found via the <code>PPID</code> column or <code>ps -o ppid= -p PID</code>. For a genuine runaway, identify it precisely with <code>ps aux --sort=-%cpu | head</code>, then decide between a graceful <code>kill PID</code> (SIGTERM, letting it clean up) and a forceful <code>kill -9 PID</code> (SIGKILL, last resort). To stop the same process from re-saturating the box, you can renice it lower priority with <code>renice +10 -p PID</code> or constrain it for good by launching it under a systemd slice with CPU and memory limits. Triage discipline reach for the single bad actor before concluding you need more hardware saves many an unnecessary capacity upgrade.</p><div class='callout'><div class='lbl'>Remember</div>Low 'free' memory is not a problem Linux caches with spare RAM; watch <strong>available</strong> instead. And a process that disappears with no log is the OOM killer's signature: <code>dmesg | grep -i killed</code> confirms it and names the victim. High <code>%wa</code> means the disk, not the CPU, is the constraint.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[5].push(
  {heading:"Performance II: Disk I/O, Latency, and Throughput", body:"<p>When CPU and memory are fine but applications crawl, storage is the usual culprit. Disk troubleshooting separates two distinct measures: <span class='keyterm'>latency</span> (how long each operation takes) and <span class='keyterm'>throughput</span> (how much data moves per second). A high-latency disk feels slow even at low throughput; a saturated link caps throughput even at low latency. Telling these apart drives the fix add IOPS for latency, add bandwidth for throughput.</p><h3>iostat and the I/O Wait Signal</h3><p>The headline indicator is <span class='keyterm'>%iowait</span> from <code>top</code> or <code>iostat</code>: it is the percentage of time the CPU sat idle waiting for I/O to complete. Sustained high iowait with idle CPU means the disk, not the processor, is the bottleneck. Drill in with <code>iostat -xz 1</code>, which prints per-device statistics every second. The columns that matter are <code>%util</code> (how busy the device is 100 percent means saturated), <code>await</code> (average milliseconds per request, the latency figure), and <code>r/s</code> plus <code>w/s</code> with their throughput in <code>rkB/s</code> and <code>wkB/s</code>.</p><table><thead><tr><th>iostat column</th><th>Meaning</th><th>Red flag</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>%util</code></td><td>Device busy time</td><td>Near 100% = saturated</td></tr><tr><td><code>await</code></td><td>Avg latency per request (ms)</td><td>High = slow disk</td></tr><tr><td><code>r/s, w/s</code></td><td>Operations per second (IOPS)</td><td>Ceiling reached</td></tr><tr><td><code>aqu-sz</code></td><td>Average queue depth</td><td>Deep queue = backlog</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Finding the Culprit with iotop</h3><p><code>iotop -o</code> shows, in real time, which <em>processes</em> are generating disk I/O, sorted by read and write rates (the <code>-o</code> flag hides idle processes). This answers the question iostat cannot: not just that the disk is busy, but <em>who</em> is hammering it a runaway backup, a database doing a full table scan, or a log spinning out of control. Pair it with <code>iostat</code> to see the device side and <code>iotop</code> to see the process side; the <code>pidstat -d 1</code> command gives the same per-process I/O view without a curses UI.</p><h3>Benchmarking with fio</h3><p>To distinguish a genuinely slow disk from a busy one, benchmark with <span class='keyterm'>fio</span> (Flexible I/O tester). A simple random-read test, <code>fio --name=test --rw=randread --bs=4k --size=1G --numjobs=4 --runtime=30 --group_reporting</code>, reports achievable IOPS, bandwidth, and latency percentiles. Comparing the result against the device's rated spec (or its baseline) tells you whether the hardware is underperforming or simply overloaded by legitimate work. Use this to validate a SAN LUN, a cloud volume's provisioned IOPS, or a suspected failing drive.</p><h3>I/O Scheduling</h3><p>The kernel <span class='keyterm'>I/O scheduler</span> orders requests to balance latency and throughput. View the active scheduler with <code>cat /sys/block/sda/queue/scheduler</code> (the bracketed name is active). For fast SSDs and NVMe, <code>none</code> or <code>mq-deadline</code> is preferred because aggressive reordering wastes effort on devices with no seek penalty; spinning disks may benefit from <code>bfq</code> for interactive fairness. Change it at runtime with <code>echo mq-deadline &gt; /sys/block/sda/queue/scheduler</code> and persist via a udev rule or kernel parameter. Choosing the right scheduler can meaningfully cut latency on the wrong-defaulted device.</p><h3>SMART Data and Failing Hardware</h3><p>When a disk is slow rather than busy and benchmarks confirm it underperforms its rating, suspect failing hardware and read the drive's own self-diagnostics with <span class='keyterm'>SMART</span>. Run <code>smartctl -a /dev/sda</code> from the smartmontools package to dump every attribute; the headline verdict is the 'SMART overall-health self-assessment test result' line, but the attributes below it tell the real story. <code>Reallocated_Sector_Ct</code> climbing above zero means the drive is silently swapping in spare sectors as the platters fail, <code>Pending_Sector</code> counts unreadable sectors awaiting reallocation, and <code>Current_Pending_Sector</code> or <code>Offline_Uncorrectable</code> rising over time is a near-certain sign of imminent death. For SSDs, watch <code>Wear_Leveling_Count</code> and <code>Media_Wearout_Indicator</code> to gauge remaining write endurance. Launch an on-demand check with <code>smartctl -t short /dev/sda</code> and read the result after a couple of minutes. Pair SMART with the kernel's view: <code>dmesg | grep -i 'I/O error'</code> or messages mentioning <code>ata</code> resets and <code>medium error</code> confirm the kernel is seeing read failures, which alongside high <code>await</code> in <code>iostat</code> separates a dying drive from one that is merely overloaded.</p><h3>Network Throughput Bottlenecks</h3><p>Storage is not the only I/O that stalls applications; a saturated or misconfigured network link produces the same 'everything is slow' complaint. Measure end-to-end throughput between two hosts with <code>iperf3 -s</code> on one and <code>iperf3 -c server</code> on the other, which reports achievable bandwidth and exposes a gigabit link that has negotiated down to 100 Mbps or a duplex mismatch flooding the wire with collisions. Confirm the negotiated speed with <code>ethtool eth0</code> and watch live interface counters with <code>ip -s link show eth0</code> or <code>sar -n DEV 1</code>, looking for rising <code>dropped</code> or <code>errors</code>. A link that benchmarks far below its rated speed, or one accumulating errors, points at cabling, a failing NIC, or an autonegotiation problem, not the application above it.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Scheduler</th><th>Best for</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>none</code></td><td>NVMe SSDs (no reordering needed)</td></tr><tr><td><code>mq-deadline</code></td><td>General SSD, latency-sensitive</td></tr><tr><td><code>bfq</code></td><td>Spinning disks, desktop fairness</td></tr></tbody></table><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div>High <code>%iowait</code> with otherwise idle CPU is the textbook 'the disk is the bottleneck' signal don't chase CPU. Use <code>iostat -xz 1</code> for the device view (look at <code>%util</code> and <code>await</code>) and <code>iotop -o</code> to find which process is responsible.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[5].push(
  {heading:"Remote Access and Certificate Troubleshooting", body:"<p>The final cluster of Domain 5 skills covers the failures that lock you out or break secure communication: SSH that will not connect, TLS certificates that browsers and clients reject, and applications that crash and need post-mortem analysis. Each has a precise diagnostic workflow, and each maps a specific error string to a specific fix.</p><h3>SSH Connection Failures</h3><p>When SSH fails, the single most useful action is to raise verbosity: <code>ssh -vvv user@host</code> prints the entire handshake key exchange, which keys are offered, and exactly where it stops. Common failure points and their fingerprints: 'Connection refused' means sshd is not running or the wrong port (check <code>ss -tlnp | grep :22</code> on the server); 'Connection timed out' means a firewall is dropping packets; 'Permission denied (publickey)' means key auth failed. Key auth most often fails due to <strong>permissions</strong> OpenSSH rejects a private key that is group/world-readable and rejects <code>authorized_keys</code> in a world-writable home. The fixes are <code>chmod 600 ~/.ssh/id_ed25519</code>, <code>chmod 700 ~/.ssh</code>, and <code>chmod 600 ~/.ssh/authorized_keys</code>. The verbose output line 'Offering public key' followed by 'Authentications that can continue' confirms the server refused that key.</p><table><thead><tr><th>SSH error</th><th>Cause</th><th>Fix</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Connection refused</td><td>sshd down / wrong port</td><td>Start sshd, check <code>ss -tlnp</code></td></tr><tr><td>Connection timed out</td><td>Firewall dropping</td><td>Open port 22 / security group</td></tr><tr><td>Permission denied (publickey)</td><td>Key perms or wrong key</td><td><code>chmod 600</code> key, 700 ~/.ssh</td></tr><tr><td>REMOTE HOST IDENTIFICATION CHANGED</td><td>Host key changed</td><td>Remove stale <code>known_hosts</code> line</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>known_hosts Warnings</h3><p>The alarming 'WARNING: REMOTE HOST IDENTIFICATION HAS CHANGED' appears when a server's host key differs from the one cached in <code>~/.ssh/known_hosts</code> either a legitimate rebuild or a man-in-the-middle attack. After verifying the change is legitimate, remove the stale entry with <code>ssh-keygen -R hostname</code> and reconnect to accept the new key. Never blindly delete the whole file or set <code>StrictHostKeyChecking no</code>, which silences a genuine security control.</p><h3>Certificate Issues</h3><p>TLS failures break HTTPS, LDAPS, and any encrypted service. The two dominant causes are an <span class='keyterm'>expired certificate</span> and a broken <span class='keyterm'>chain of trust</span> (a missing intermediate CA). Inspect a certificate's validity with <code>openssl x509 -in cert.pem -noout -dates</code> (shows notBefore/notAfter) and verify a live server with <code>openssl s_client -connect host:443 -showcerts</code>, which prints the full chain and any verification error. <code>openssl verify -CAfile chain.pem cert.pem</code> confirms the chain validates. Errors map cleanly: 'certificate has expired' means renew it; 'unable to get local issuer certificate' means the intermediate is missing concatenate it into the server's chain file. A name mismatch ('hostname doesn't match') means the certificate's CN/SAN does not cover the address used.</p><table><thead><tr><th>openssl error</th><th>Meaning</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>certificate has expired</td><td>Past notAfter renew</td></tr><tr><td>unable to get local issuer certificate</td><td>Missing intermediate CA in chain</td></tr><tr><td>self-signed certificate</td><td>Not trusted by a known CA</td></tr><tr><td>hostname mismatch</td><td>CN/SAN does not cover the address</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Application Crashes: coredumpctl and strace</h3><p>When an application crashes, systemd-coredump captures a core. List recent crashes with <code>coredumpctl list</code> and inspect one in a debugger with <code>coredumpctl gdb &lt;PID&gt;</code> to see the backtrace at the moment of death. For a process that misbehaves without crashing hangs, fails to open a file, or loops attach <code>strace -p PID</code> to watch its system calls live; an <code>open('/etc/foo', ...) = -1 ENOENT</code> or <code>EACCES</code> instantly reveals a missing or unreadable file. For library-loading failures, <code>ldd /path/to/binary</code> shows 'not found' against any missing shared object.</p><h3>Server-Side SSH and Verbose Logging</h3><p>Verbose client output (<code>ssh -vvv</code>) explains what the client sees, but when the client says only 'Permission denied' the truth often lives in the server's log. Watch it live during a failed attempt with <code>journalctl -u sshd -f</code>, which prints sshd's own reason: 'Authentication refused: bad ownership or modes for directory /home/user/.ssh' names the permission problem precisely, 'User user not allowed because not listed in AllowUsers' reveals an access-control directive, and 'maximum authentication attempts exceeded' means the client offered too many wrong keys. The server config in <code>/etc/ssh/sshd_config</code> holds the policy that the client cannot see: <code>PubkeyAuthentication</code>, <code>PasswordAuthentication</code>, <code>PermitRootLogin</code>, and <code>AllowUsers</code>/<code>AllowGroups</code> all silently reject connections that violate them. After editing that file, validate the syntax with <code>sshd -t</code> before restarting OpenSSH so a typo does not lock everyone out, then <code>systemctl restart sshd</code>. The golden rule when changing SSH on a remote box is to keep your existing session open and test the change in a second connection a broken config that you only discover after logging out can strand you. For deeper handshake analysis, raise the daemon's own verbosity with <code>LogLevel DEBUG3</code> temporarily, reproduce, then revert.</p><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div>A user's key-based SSH login suddenly fails with 'Permission denied (publickey)' after a home-directory restore. <code>ssh -vvv</code> shows the key offered and rejected. On the server, <code>ls -ld ~/.ssh</code> reveals mode <code>0775</code> too open. <code>chmod 700 ~/.ssh; chmod 600 ~/.ssh/authorized_keys</code> and login works instantly OpenSSH was refusing the loose permissions.</div>"}
);
